text: I expect that Disney will change the feel of the characters and the plots to match their established norm.    The broadway production used the Grimm version of these stories, whereas Disney always used the cleaned up versions.  (We saw their T.V. show do this with "Once Upon A Time.")  So, we won't get the sexual allusions of Red Riding Hood.  We won't see Cinderella resurrecting the ghost of her mother, nor birds pecking out the eyes of her step mother.   We won't see Rapunzel living, impoverished, in the desert with her bastard children.   And so on.     I'm guessing that the morals of parenthood presented in the broadway version will be ignored as well.

text: Everyone's wondering if there's going to be singing. Of course there is. It's obvious, especially when you notice that some of the music is to the tune of "Stay With Me," which they wouldn't do if they weren't going to include the song. Anyway, I have a different question. Well, more of an observation: this is really dark for a Disney movie. *SPOILER ALERT* I believe that Disney is keeping Rapunzel alive, but still, tons of people die. Don't get me wrong, I love the idea of Disney adapting this musical and keeping all of the themes, but when you think about the fact that this is the studio where every single good character gets a happy ending, this movie will be really dark in comparison.

text: This is a terrible trailer for the film.  I saw a version of this last weekend, only it had a tacked-on scene of Meryl Streep singing at the end.  TOTALLY DID NOT CONNECT WITH THE AUDIENCE!  Absolutely everyone in the room unfamiliar with it beforehand assumed it was a kids' movie, then were completely confused when Meryl showed up singing a slow, melancholy number in close-up.  It just elicited giggles.  Very confusing tone that failed to display the film's strengths (except the cast, perhaps, though they could have done better).  Tips: *Lead with Stephen Sondheim's name, not "From the director/producer of..."  More people will recognize that it's a musical at the mention of Sondheim than will from oblique indications by anonymous credits! (<-A paradoxical term if I ever had to write one!) *It's a musical!  Put that prominently in the trailer rather than tacking it on literally after the credits!  (Or not at all in this version!)  How do you make a trailer for a musical and not show anyone singing?! *Establish the premise/story, not just a bunch of scenes.  I saw a production of the musical years ago, yet have no idea what this movie is about other than the fairy tale mash-up.

text: If any of you are thinking about seeing this, here's my review. (I saw the original musical as well) So if you have never heard of Into The Woods before, than it's a story about four well known fairytale characters: Cinderella, Rapunzel, Little Red Ridinghood, and Jack from Jack and The Beanstalk along with a witch (Gothel from Rapunzel) and two new characters the Baker and his wife. The Baker and his wife must go on a journey to collect four ingredients to make a potion for the witch so that they can have a kid; the cow as white as milk, the cape as red as blood, the hair as yellow as corn, and the slipper as pure as gold. It's a story about being careful what you wish for and that things aren't always as they seem. It's rated PG, but I wouldn't recommend bringing small children as it's pretty long, and they might get bored. The actors all did a fantastic job, I was especially impressed with the baker's wife, Jack, the baker, and the wolf. Of course Meryl Streep was beyond fantastic, she made an absolutely perfect witch. The singing was incredible, some of my favorites were Stay With Me, On The Steps Of The Palace, Giants In The Sky, I Know Things Now, No One Is Alone, and the Prologue. The Princes absolutely nailed Agony. I had a couple of issues with the movie, mainly all in the ending. The ending was very rushed, even though some songs were taken out. Rapunzel did not die or go insane, but lives happily with her prince instead. The reprise of Agony was removed, although START OF SPOILER Cinderella's prince still had an 'affair' with the baker's wife. END OF SPOILER When Little Red Ridinghood was swallowed by the wolf, the way that was done was a bit cheesy. All in all, on a scale from 1-10, I'd give it a 9. It was very good, especially since Into The Woods is a tough show to put on. (My cousin was the witch in her school's production) Anyways, I hoped this helped!
